metadata.name: Geologic #173
metadata.description:
This series was born from a desire to depict imagined landscapes from literal building 'blocks', and the fundamental concepts of stone, sea, and sky.

Each scene pairs a subtle nod to geological processes with the fleeting mood unveiled by weather and time of day.

metadata.name: TROUBLEMaker #13
metadata.description:
TROUBLEMaker displays the struggle between two line drawing algorithms, one that wants to paint an ordered radial composition, and another that wants to mess with it. The result is a somehow circular line drawing, which resembles a sort of strange, hand-drawn eye.

This piece is dedicated to my little brother, by messing with all my Lego constructions when we were kids, he thought me more than anybody else about how the interplay of order and chaos is fundamental to creativity and life.

------------------------

Original artwork by Roberto Ranon aka Doble. Made between February and April 2022 using p5.js, canvas-sketch, and love.

The 50% of primary sales is automatically redirected to KT1DWnLiUkNtAQDErXxudFEH63JC6mqg3HEx, a donation smart contract built by FxHash & Versum that supports various ONGs that are helping the people of Ukraine.

May run quite slow on some devices/browsers - in the case, I suggest to use the time to relax and appreciate the animation.

In full screen, pressing Cmd + S or Ctrl + S will save a 4096x4096 image of the artwork.

metadata.name: Mei(梅) #17
metadata.description:
Mei(梅):

"Mei" is an oriental art piece featuring the imagery of plum blossom, a symbol of courage and perseverance in traditional Chinese culture.

The generative system at the backend of "Mei" is an exploration of this cultural symbol by modern art language. The basic elements of the paintings are merely circles and enclosed flow field shapes. A great variety of short and light strokes of such elements are used across the paintings. Xuan paper is occasionally used as background, which is a painting material since the Tang dynasty.

Mei's outputs span different stages of plum blossom from winter to spring. The scene also changes from a calm day to snowy or even stormy weather. The consistent yet complex senses and feelings reflected are surprisingly versatile.

metadata.name: Electric Rays #15
metadata.description: An elegant, intricate set of moving and static rays, with a central light and a dual emission. It has many variants depending on the generated hash, from circular setup to star-like and flower-like. The color changes from crimson/reddish to all the color spectrum. It is based on the sin/cos functions, tied with the framecount parameter to originate the movement. Using the p5.js library

metadata.name: The Ocean Waves #18
metadata.description:
Ocean waves in calm or stormy skies. Spray, and the occasional buoy passes by.

Large and rolling waves are generated at the back and get more turbulent as they get closer to the viewer. A stripe of sunlight varies in position from towards the back to the front. The highest waves create spray. Everyone once and a while, a buoy or two (or more!) will pass by. The background color is related to the buoy color to make it more harmonious.

metadata.name: reborn #103
metadata.description:
This is an album of cities too ideal to ever materialise.

It consists of 256 algorithmically generated plans that resemble drawings of Vincenzo Scamozzi, Pietro Cataneo, Filarete and other theorists of the Italian Renaissance. The cities differ in size, the grid of the streets, the landscape around them and the people that inhabit their utopian walls. They carry names that are Italian exonyms of real European cities, drawing a vision of a different world that enacts a mixture of military perfection with social superiority. Flawless, harmonious, unconquerable and utterly impossible.

History brought us many theories about ideal cities, but very few examples exist today. Italian Palmanova or Polish Zamość are the few to remind us how hard it is to shape reality according to ideals. When confronted with the material world, its idealism becomes the city's grates foe.

To zoom, press a mouse button over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: Layered Landscapes #12
metadata.description:
Layered Landscapes explores representing imaginary landscapes through line art designed for output with a pen plotter.

It supports these variations:

Hill Contours: 4 layers
Dark Foreground: 50% chance the first contour is overprinted for darker darks
Sky: straight or curved
fog: 0, 1 or 2 layers
trees: 1 to 7

Press "s" to download the SVG.

Output is designed for 6" x 4".

metadata.name: Lepidoptera #53

I love trying to capture the textures and colors found in nature and reproduce them with code. Lepidoptera is inspired by the species of the same name.

metadata.name: Skravert #85
metadata.description:
‘Skravert’ - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‘The act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area’.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021
